summary: It's funny that people really think Jon will just give up his Stark identity like that.  He always wanted to be a Stark, and...
question: It's funny that people really think Jon will just give up his Stark identity like that.  He always wanted to be a Stark, and just because he doesn't have the Stark name doesn't mean he is not a Stark. He was raised a Stark, and he will always see himself as one, regardless the Targ  reveal. He will never stop being a Stark, and that's what the symbol is supposed to represent.
answer:
I mean, I do get why people say that. In season 7 alone he said, twice, “I am not a Stark.” But I take that to mean, “I know I’m illegitimate. I don’t really belong in the Stark family.” I interpret it as a self-conscious thing.

But you’re right–Jon was raised by Starks and his ideals and morals molded by Ned. SO I think the Stark sigil will always represent him.

At the same time, I do think it’s significant that he can adopt the entwined sigils with Dany because of that lack of true belonging to the Stark family that he evidently still feels as recently as last season. He hasn’t totally found his niche yet, but he will by being part of Dany’s family and bringing her into the fold of the Starks, too. Like he told Theon, he can be both.
